1
00:00:00,125 --> 00:00:08,000
To this day, as I told you at the beginning, I am afraid
when I pass by it, every time I pass by I feel tense and anxious

2
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:15,000
In the disciplinary cell, my blood sugar started dropping,
to this day, it still drops sometimes

3
00:00:15,916 --> 00:00:22,208
Once I got very tense, I do not want to say I was brave
or a hero, honestly I was not scared, but I was tense

4
00:00:22,291 --> 00:00:25,208
Unsettled, meaning annoyed, suffocated by this place,
tight and suffocating

5
00:00:26,333 --> 00:00:30,541
My blood sugar started dropping,
to this day it still affects me

6
00:00:31,416 --> 00:00:35,625
The scars on my feet,
my knee took six months of treatment

7
00:00:36,041 --> 00:00:41,916
And this cheekbone was broken,
the mark stayed for a long time, it never went away

8
00:00:42,291 --> 00:00:46,333
My hand here, to this day, because of one time
on the <i>balingo</i> [hoist for suspension]

9
00:00:46,500 --> 00:00:50,458
Of course the balingo is a hoist shaped like this,
my hand to this very moment

10
00:00:50,916 --> 00:00:55,708
My hand here is not like my other hand,
sometimes it hurts a lot

11
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:03,208
Interviewer: What were the other methods
of torture they used?

12
00:01:04,750 --> 00:01:09,458
The other method of torture was the disciplinary cell,
and it was worse than the beatings

13
00:01:09,916 --> 00:01:13,375
Worse than anything,
it was humiliation upon humiliation

14
00:01:13,458 --> 00:01:20,208
Interviewer: I mean the devices, like
the balingo, and <i>shabeh</i> [suspension]

15
00:01:20,458 --> 00:01:27,541
Everything you can imagine, of course there was a torture
method that was both humiliation and torture

16
00:01:27,916 --> 00:01:32,875
When you leave the interrogation, they take you out,
he tells you, walk on your own

17
00:01:34,250 --> 00:01:38,375
You are blindfolded and do not know where you are going,
and if you hit the wall, they beat you immediately

18
00:01:38,541 --> 00:01:41,333
Sometimes, I remember once
I hit the wall and fell

19
00:01:41,916 --> 00:01:48,291
Both of them, there were two, started beating me,
and I immediately got up, I had to get up quickly

20
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:55,125
The rest of the torture methods, they used everything,
only electricity they did not use, everything else they did

21
00:01:56,041 --> 00:01:59,791
Interviewer: Was torture applied to all prisoners?
Or only to specific people?

22
00:01:59,833 --> 00:02:06,416
No, everyone, everyone was tortured,
everyone I believe, I do not think anyone entered here

23
00:02:06,458 --> 00:02:10,833
Into this place as a prisoner and can say
I was not beaten, impossible

24
00:02:11,958 --> 00:02:16,875
Interviewer: Did you hear about any women
being held in the prison? Or hear women being tortured?

25
00:02:17,458 --> 00:02:24,166
No, I did not hear that, but they said before my time
there was one female prisoner, I heard about her

26
00:02:24,750 --> 00:02:30,166
Once, they took my friend who is a nurse,
and he put an IV drip for her

27
00:02:30,375 --> 00:02:35,416
He even said she extended her hand through
a window, but without him seeing her

28
00:02:35,708 --> 00:02:40,291
And he set up the IV,
that is all, that is what I heard

29
00:02:40,333 --> 00:02:44,833
But while I was in this place,
I never heard women's voices, nothing at all

30
00:02:46,291 --> 00:02:53,291
Interviewer: Who were the people responsible for torture?
Where were they from? What was their accent?

31
00:02:54,541 --> 00:02:59,833
The interrogator was from the area,
and the two guards were mostly from the area as well

32
00:03:00,708 --> 00:03:04,333
Their accent was from this region,
I do not know his name of course

33
00:03:05,416 --> 00:03:09,250
I have no idea what his name was,
they would call him Abu Abdullah, that is all

34
00:03:12,666 --> 00:03:17,083
Interviewer: Did you hear of any prisoner
who died under torture here in the prison?

35
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:23,583
Before my imprisonment, yes I heard,
I heard about two people who died, they were cousins

36
00:03:24,583 --> 00:03:28,166
Even when their family paid,
there were three of them imprisoned

37
00:03:28,916 --> 00:03:35,500
They released one of them in exchange for the fact
that the other two had died under torture, and they paid blood money

38
00:03:36,208 --> 00:03:44,083
They paid their blood money as compensation for their
death under torture, and pardoned the third cousin, who was the brother of one of the deceased

39
00:03:44,166 --> 00:03:46,708
Interviewer: Can you give us
the names of those people?

40
00:03:47,833 --> 00:03:50,625
Which names?
Interviewer: The people who died under torture

41
00:03:52,291 --> 00:03:59,125
Names of people who died under torture? I do not know their
names, because those three were not from this area

42
00:03:59,291 --> 00:04:02,500
From around the area,
I do not know their exact names

43
00:04:02,875 --> 00:04:09,875
The way they would deliver sentences, for example,
I remember an incident with a person, may God have mercy on him

44
00:04:10,708 --> 00:04:17,166
When they made him read his own execution sentence,
they started laughing while he was crying

45
00:04:17,541 --> 00:04:20,416
And they were laughing,
they did that to provoke him

46
00:04:21,083 --> 00:04:26,208
This is something I did not witness personally,
but someone who was an eyewitness told me about it

47
00:04:26,416 --> 00:04:28,708
To this very moment,
this incident still affects me
